Sure! In C programming, an if/then statement is used to execute a block of code based on a condition. The syntax for an if/then statement is as follows:

if (condition) {
  // Code to execute if the condition is true
}

The condition is typically a Boolean expression that evaluates to either true or false. If the condition is true, the code within the curly braces will be executed. If the condition is false, the code within the curly braces will not be executed.

For example, the following code checks if a variable named "age" is greater than 18 and then prints a message:

if (age > 18) {
  printf("You are eligible to vote.");
}

In this example, the condition is "age > 18," which evaluates to true if the value of the "age" variable is greater than 18. If the condition is true, the code within the curly braces will be executed, and the message "You are eligible to vote." will be printed.

It's important to note that the if/then statement can be combined with other control flow statements, such as else, switch, and do-while, to create more complex programs.
